I'm not a fan of the police, but my characters and I don't need to share the same ideals.
As for the moral issue, assume the hypothetical police officers to be otherwise good people. They have been told
>"This house is a meth lab. Go raid it."
The officers conducting the raid don't know what the reality is or is not. All they know is what they are told. So now, they perform the raid, and they raid the wrong house. John Doe, the homeowner and all around swell guy, awakes to someone kicking his door in at 3am with guns and flashlights. It may not even register that these are the police, so aiming to defend himself and his property, he opens fire. The police, assuming this to be the right house, are now being shot at. They return fire, and kill John Doe.
A terrible thing has happened, and there is quite literally nothing the officers on the ground could have done to prevent it.
There are parties that should be held responsible, and in the hypothetical cop circumstance, it is whoever issued the wrong address. The ground pounders follow orders. It's their job.
Much the same circumstances exist in war. When an artillery crew is told "adjust gun to X degrees by Y degrees, and fire five rounds", that's all they know. They don't know where the rounds will hit. Later, when they find out they bombed an orphanage, that crew literally had no idea where they were shooting, so the responsibility falls on whoever knew where they would shoot, and gave the order.

But, the best part of all of this is that you can disagree entirely. Perhaps it is morally reprehensible, and without justification. Perhaps the men in these hypothetical situations should have questioned the orders to maintain moral certainty of their actions. Perhaps Mike, in his blind panic, shot an innocent man who otherwise could have been talked down, and should be held responsible by being charged for murder. I don't want to hold your hand through the moral questions. The answers are up to you :D
